        <!-- What is DHW -->
        <section class="content-section">
            <h2>
                <span data-lang="en">What is DHW?</span>
                <span data-lang="ja">DHWã¨ã¯</span>
            </h2>
            <p>
                <span data-lang="en">
                    DHW (Degree Heating Weeks) is a metric developed by NOAA Coral Reef Watch 
                    to quantify accumulated thermal stress on corals. It measures how much heat 
                    has built up over the past 12 weeks above the bleaching threshold (MMM + 1Â°C).
                </span>
                <span data-lang="ja">
                    DHWï¼ˆDegree Heating Weeksï¼šåº¦é€±ï¼‰ã¯ã€ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ã¸ã®ç´¯ç©ç†±ã‚¹ãƒˆãƒ¬ã‚¹ã‚’å®šé‡åŒ–ã™ã‚‹ãŸã‚ã«
                    NOAA Coral Reef WatchãŒé–‹ç™ºã—ãŸæŒ‡æ¨™ã§ã™ã€‚éå»12é€±é–“ã§ç™½åŒ–é–¾å€¤ï¼ˆMMM + 1Â°Cï¼‰ã‚’
                    è¶…ãˆãŸç†±ãŒã©ã‚Œã ã‘è“„ç©ã•ã‚ŒãŸã‹ã‚’æ¸¬å®šã—ã¾ã™ã€‚
                </span>
            </p>
            <p>
                <span data-lang="en">
                    The unit is Â°C-weeks. For example, 1Â°C above threshold for 4 weeks = 4 DHW, 
                    or 2Â°C above threshold for 2 weeks = 4 DHW. The higher the DHW, 
                    the greater the accumulated stress and bleaching risk.
                </span>
                <span data-lang="ja">
                    å˜ä½ã¯Â°C-weeksï¼ˆåº¦é€±ï¼‰ã§ã™ã€‚ä¾‹ãˆã°ã€é–¾å€¤ã‚’1Â°Cè¶…ãˆã‚‹çŠ¶æ…‹ãŒ4é€±é–“ç¶šãã¨4 DHWã€
                    2Â°Cè¶…ãˆã‚‹çŠ¶æ…‹ãŒ2é€±é–“ç¶šã„ã¦ã‚‚4 DHWã¨ãªã‚Šã¾ã™ã€‚
                    DHWãŒé«˜ã„ã»ã©ã€è“„ç©ã•ã‚ŒãŸã‚¹ãƒˆãƒ¬ã‚¹ã¨ç™½åŒ–ãƒªã‚¹ã‚¯ãŒå¤§ãããªã‚Šã¾ã™ã€‚
                </span>
            </p>
        </section>

